{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"811bb8b8-e6dc-469a-aea8-472e3c35fb80","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must use stdio transport (e.g., via `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package with `.WithStdioServerTransport()`).\n- **Don't** write to `Console.Out` for logging — use `Console.Error` or `ILogger` instead, since stdout is reserved for MCP protocol messages.\n\nIf you've already built the project and prefer running the compiled binary:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Debug/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8b7babe-0471-475b-b5be-2c22f4a938b7","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"D030:15785A:1416183:16971FE:6A0673EE"},"id":"231354e4-c86d-4b21-b320-28fcff788593","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:16:38.710Z","parentId":"810e69e8-d63f-47f2-a899-adfe98d90800"}
